  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3053563754" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3053563754" />
    <a title="Susan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5747295-susan"><img alt="Susan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442606035p2/5747295.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3053563754?book_show_action=true">Dec 21, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Susan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Susan" href="/user/show/5747295-susan">Susan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3053563754" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1049794863001871852">In the past year, I read “On the Occasion of My Last Afternoon” by Kaye Gibbons, and enjoyed it. So, while recently looking through available books to download on my kindle from the library, I came across another Gibbons book, “Charms for the Easy Life.”<br/><br/>This book takes place during the 1940s and follows the lives of three women: Charlie Kate, an outspoken self-taught physician; her daughter Sophia who is suffering from the abandonment of her husband, and Sophia’s daughter Margaret. The three liv</span>
  <span id="freeText1049794863001871852" style="display:none">In the past year, I read “On the Occasion of My Last Afternoon” by Kaye Gibbons, and enjoyed it. So, while recently looking through available books to download on my kindle from the library, I came across another Gibbons book, “Charms for the Easy Life.”<br /><br />This book takes place during the 1940s and follows the lives of three women: Charlie Kate, an outspoken self-taught physician; her daughter Sophia who is suffering from the abandonment of her husband, and Sophia’s daughter Margaret. The three live together, and we follow them through several years.<br /><br />Charlie Kate reminded me a lot of the Dowager Countess on Downton Abbey: popping off one-liners and supremely in-charge and sure of herself: “I have read two books a week for thirty years. I am satisfied that I know everything.” She is famous in town for helping cure many people who couldn’t be helped by the conventional doctor. One man she helped said, “I did not care to die. I like being by myself too much. I’m not ready to go be around everybody that’s ever died. That’s a lot of people.” Gibbons has a wonderful way with language and captures many bits like this that I enjoyed savoring.<br /><br />Our three females had a house that sounded great to me: “In our house, the point of reading and learning was neither to impress outsiders nor to get a job or a husband, nothing like that. It had nothing to do with anybody but the three of us. When a good book was in the house the place fairly vibrated.”<br /><br />The book had a few issues, I thought. First, while Charlie Kate is really strong and tough, and Margaret ostensibly is the same, Sophia and Margaret spend a lot of time waiting for men to do this or that, or in Sophia’s case pining after a man who seems to have a hard time making up his mind. Margaret is so in her grandmother’s thrall that she can’t imagine leaving home to go to college (Charlie Kate says, “I’m afraid that if you go somewhere you don’t want to go, you’ll be miserable and you won’t learn a drop. Your mother’s stubborn nature will surely blossom in you and take over.” And then she smiled and said, “And you’d be wasting my money.”). She waits for her grandmother to explain her life to her, which seems incongruous with her strong intelligence.<br /><br />I also am not a big fan of Gibbon’s titles. I commented on this on my review of “On the Occasion …” and same thing here — the “charm” referred to is mentioned quite near the end of the book, and to me didn’t have a lot of significance. Of course, it’s entirely possible that I’m missing some deep point here 🙂<br /><br />Still, overall I enjoyed this book and especially Gibbon’s writing. “There is no alone here,” she says of the three women’s house, and that is how I felt reading “Charms for the Easy Life.”</span>
  <a data-text-id="1049794863001871852" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review3053563754">
  <td colspan="2">
